    "Step 0: Idle",
    "Step 1: Thinking\n  [{ Id = 149411e9-e0a5-41f4-9c7f-ced54d4a079c\n     CorrelationId = CorrelationId 3d0b8cde-298c-4620-b907-e06596bbcf6f\n     Sender = System\n     Receiver = Some (Agent (AgentId 0f2ec539-a795-4e0c-86ef-e3a1dba1cf79))\n     Performative = Request\n     Intent = Some Coding\n     Constraints = { MaxTokens = None\n                     MaxComplexity = None\n                     Timeout = None\n                     KnowledgeBoundary = [] }\n     Ontology = None\n     Language = \u0022text\u0022\n     Content =\n      \u0022### Task Summary\n\n**Goal:** Develop an F# program that uses a multi-LLM agent approach to transcribe and summarize audio recordings from virtual focus groups.\n\n**Constraints:**\n1. Handle various audio formats (e.g., MP3, WAV).\n2. Utilize different language models for transcription and summarization.\n3. Robust error handling for reliable processing of audio files.\n\n**Validation Criteria:**\n- Successfully transcribe and summarize at least 50% of audio samples from virtual focus groups.\n- Correct handling of different audio formats.\n- Robust error management.\n\n### Tools to Use\nThe program must use the following tools:\n1. \u0060fsharp_eval\u0060: For evaluating F# code.\n2. \u0060switch_model\u0060: To switch between language models for transcription and summarization.\n3. \u0060http_get\u0060: For fetching necessary data if needed.\n4. \u0060save_note\u0060 and \u0060recall_note\u0060: For saving and recalling notes during processing.\n5. Error handling tools like \u0060try_catch\u0060 or custom error handling mechanisms.\n\n### Steps to Implement\n\n1. **Audio Transcription:**\n   - Use the \u0060fsharp_eval\u0060 tool to call a language model for transcription.\n   - Switch models as needed based on audio format or other criteria using \u0060switch_model\u0060.\n\n2. **Error Handling:**\n   - Implement robust error handling around the transcription process.\n   - Save notes during errors and recall them later if needed.\n\n3. **Audio Summarization:**\n   - Use another language model for summarizing the transcribed text.\n   - Ensure that the summarization model is switched appropriately.\n\n4. **Validation:**\n   - Test the program with various audio samples to ensure it handles different formats correctly.\n   - Verify that error handling works as expected and that at least 50% of samples are successfully transcribed and summarized.\n\n### Potential Challenges\n- Handling different audio formats efficiently.\n- Ensuring robust error management across multiple stages of processing.\n- Switching between language models seamlessly for transcription and summarization.\n\n### Final Solution\n\nTo achieve the goal, the F# program should be structured as follows:\n\n1. **Initialize Environment:**\n   - Load necessary tools using \u0060load_skill\u0060.\n   - Ensure all required models are available using \u0060switch_model\u0060.\n\n2. **Transcription Loop:**\n   - For each audio file:\n     - Use \u0060fsharp_eval\u0060 to call the transcription model.\n     - Handle errors gracefully and save notes if needed.\n\n3. **Summarization Loop:**\n   - For each transcribed text:\n     - Use another language model for summarization.\n     - Save and recall notes during summarization steps.\n\n4. **Validation:**\n   - Test with a diverse set of audio files to ensure reliability.\n   - Verify that error handling is robust and that the program meets the validation criteria.\n\n### Conclusion\n\nThe F# program will be a multi-LLM agent system capable of transcribing and summarizing audio recordings from virtual focus groups. By leveraging tools like \u0060fsharp_eval\u0060, \u0060switch_model\u0060, and proper error handling, the program will ensure reliable processing across different audio formats and robust error management.\u0022\n     Timestamp = 2025-12-28 8:48:55 AM\n     Metadata = map [] }]",
